mouth), Protactile uses the space on the receiver's body instead (relying on the receiver's unimpaired sense of proprioception). This space is called contact space, and it is one of the features of Protactile that has led some linguists to call it an emerging language instead of merely a variation of ASL. The constraints of Protactile are different from ASL, demonstrating that it has unique rules and patterns, not just a modified lexicon (2). However, not all linguists believe that Protactile should be considered its own language. Some believe that there are elements of ASL missing from Protactile, while others consider it to be more like a dialect of ASL than a fully separate language (3). %0a%3c %0a%3c An interesting feature of Protactile is seen in something called backchanneling. Backchanneling gives feedback to a person as they're speaking. In a conversation between hearing individuals, backchanneling might include someone saying "uh-huh" to indicate that they're paying attention or laughing to let others know that they understood a joke. In a conversation between sighted individuals, backchanneling could involve a person nodding to show agreement or raising their eyebrows to communicate surprise. Because DeafBlind people don't have full access to visual or auditory forms of backchanneling, Protactile replaces them with tactile cues such as tapping a person's arm to confirm understanding (4). %0a%3c %0a%3c Currently, most Protactile users are adults and very few DeafBlind children have access to Protactile. Earlier this fall, a team of researchers led by Dr. Deanna Gagne of Gallaudet University was awarded a five-year grant of $2.5 million from the National Institutes of Health for this very purpose. This project will support the acquisition of Protactile in children ages 0-5 years old, with the goal of learning how DeafBlind children can learn Protactile (5). %0a%3c %0a%3c (1) https://www.opb.org/article/2022/01/05/new-language-for-deaf-blind-born-in-nor